, Skotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"1410–1456":"1410–1456","1390–1456":"1390–1456","1418–1491":"1418–1491","1433–1470":"1433–1470","1375–1430":"1375–1430","1370–Female":"1370–Overleden","1456":"1456","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1375":"1375","after 25 May 1430":"na 25 mei 1430","1470":"1470","1370":"1370","1491":"1491","1418":"1418","1390":"1390","Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1410–1456":"1410–1456","1390–1456":"1390–1456","1418–1491":"1418–1491","1433–1470":"1433–1470","1375–1430":"1375–1430","1370–Female":"1370–Deceased","1456":"1456","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1375":"1375","after 25 May 1430":"after 25 May 1430","1470":"1470","1370":"1370","1491":"1491","1418":"1418","1390":"1390","Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Berkeley was born in 1410, in Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh Barclay 5th of Kilbirnie, was 35 and his mother, Ellen Boyd, was 40. He had at least 1 son with Janet De Keith. He died in 1456, in his hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1410–1456":"1410–1456","1390–1456":"1390–1456","1418–1491":"1418–1491","1433–1470":"1433–1470","1375–1430":"1375–1430","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1456":"1456","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1375":"1375","after 25 May 1430":"pärast 25. maid 1430","1470":"1470","1370":"1370","1491":"1491","1418":"1418","1390":"1390","Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1410–1456":"1410–1456","1390–1456":"1390–1456","1418–149